        <div class="research-content">
          <h2 class="research-title">New Religiosity and the Digital Study of Eudaimonia</h2>
          <p>Between 2025-27, I am a co-PI (along with Suzanne Newcombe) on a John Templeton Foundation-funded, 1.6-million-euro grant called “New Religiosity and the Digital Study of Eudaimonia” (project # 63357). The project explores a range of key variables relating to religion and wellbeing in a global comparative context. By compiling the world’s largest, most diverse data set on new religiosity, the aim is to make quantitative inferences between ethnographically- and historically-granulated variables and individual eudaimonia, societal flourishing, and new religiosity beyond self-reporting individual affect. We aim to enliven debates about what counts as new religiosity and what underlying structures are correlated with prosocial personal, financial, and societal outcomes. My role is to collect ethnographic data from 200 scholars of East-, Southeast- and South Asian new religions. I also use a citizen science paradigm to collect data via religious group members with ‘insider’ expertise within specific new religions that are not currently represented in scholarship. As part of this project, we will publish an ethnographic film, museum exhibition and research catalog.</p>
          <a href="https://www.newreligiosity.org/" class="research-btn">Read more</a>
        </div>
